460
00:44:17,887 --> 00:44:21,912
So we wanted the right mood and atmosphere while listening to his first song.

461
00:44:21,912 --> 00:44:25,095
We decided to have a song from the streets on a flip of a coin.

462
00:44:31,840 --> 00:44:34,902
The player enters Sean's room, discovers his universe.

463
00:44:34,902 --> 00:44:41,326
It's quite similar as the scene you've just seen with Max from Left 4 Dead 1.

464
00:44:41,326 --> 00:44:44,848
Sean can listen to music while doing his stuff.

465
00:45:04,344 --> 00:45:06,308
I don't totally suck.

466
00:45:06,308 --> 00:45:15,105
Somewhere up the line, a girl in the world, she's waiting for a boy.

467
00:45:19,680 --> 00:45:23,504
So you can hear the character singing or trying to sing on top of the song.

468
00:45:23,504 --> 00:45:28,909
Again we have asked our actor Gonzalo Martin to sing during the voice recording.

469
00:45:28,909 --> 00:45:36,416
He was quite stressed about that, but it gives this great feeling you have when alone in

470
00:45:36,416 --> 00:45:39,719
your bedroom or in your car, you sing very badly.

471
00:45:39,719 --> 00:45:43,082
You all know this moment, I think.

472
00:45:44,594 --> 00:45:50,095
So to achieve proper synchronization between the song lyrics and Shun voices,

473
00:45:50,095 --> 00:45:58,437
we use the Wwise Music Custom Cue system by setting every moment we want Shun to sing.

474
00:45:58,437 --> 00:46:05,398
We also asked our audio programmer to implement callbacks from his custom cues in Halloween blueprints,

475
00:46:05,398 --> 00:46:10,099
allowing us to get them in real time and trigger the relevant voices from Shun.

476
00:46:15,145 --> 00:46:20,851
I just wanted to show you the overall blueprint that was handled by Yannick Tassin, the sound

477
00:46:20,851 --> 00:46:22,853
designer responsible of this scene.

478
00:46:22,853 --> 00:46:29,159
We had to manage checkpoints, 2D, 3D versions of the song, as well as ensure that our system

479
00:46:29,159 --> 00:46:31,281
went through the global voice manager of the game.

480
00:46:36,681 --> 00:46:43,385
Another quick example of our characters interacting with a song is at the end of the first episode.

481
00:46:43,385 --> 00:46:52,451
Sean and Daniel are safe in a motel room and the player has something terrible to announce to his little brother.

482
00:46:52,451 --> 00:46:59,716
When you are going back to the room to do so, Daniel has launched the TV and just wants to dance on the bed.

483
00:46:59,716 --> 00:47:01,617
We use Block Party's song, Banquet.

484
00:47:07,556 --> 00:47:14,239
Okay, don't think about it.

485
00:47:14,239 --> 00:47:19,121
Just tell Daniel the truth.

486
00:47:19,121 --> 00:47:20,782
Are you kidding me?

487
00:47:20,782 --> 00:47:23,463
Remember that song?

488
00:47:23,463 --> 00:47:26,464
Come on, dance!

489
00:47:50,175 --> 00:47:56,017
So in this specific case, as the player can take all the time he wants to make his choice,

490
00:47:56,017 --> 00:47:58,558
it pushed us to create an infinite loop in the song.

491
00:47:58,558 --> 00:48:04,101
So we have split the track in three segments, intro, loop, and end.

492
00:48:04,101 --> 00:48:08,243
So the song feeling is preserved.

493
00:48:08,243 --> 00:48:15,166
On top of that, we use also a 3D 2D effect when both Sean and Daniel are dancing together.

494
00:48:15,166 --> 00:48:19,388
And the music will of course stop if Sean gets out of the bed and switches off the TV.

495
00:48:26,898 --> 00:48:30,280
So we are very lucky to use music from a lot of great artists.

496
00:48:30,280 --> 00:48:32,861
We wanted to thank all of them again today.

497
00:48:32,861 --> 00:48:34,102
We thank a lot of people today.

498
00:48:34,102 --> 00:48:38,825
But it's a very long process to have all those artists involved,

499
00:48:38,825 --> 00:48:42,267
and here is a quick description when everything works.

500
00:48:42,267 --> 00:48:46,369
As already explained, for the selection of tracks of the game,

501
00:48:46,369 --> 00:48:48,790
we gather titles from a lot of artists.

502
00:48:50,138 --> 00:49:00,947
For each track, I keep as much information as possible, the meanings of the lyrics, the feeling listening to it, the beats of the song, but also the backstory of the artist and the track itself.

503
00:49:00,947 --> 00:49:13,578
It ends in a huge file full of song titles. As soon as I select a title, we will test it with the audio team and also the camera team, if it's a sequence.

504
00:49:13,578 --> 00:49:18,682
If we are happy, we can ask for a price and finalize approval and contract.

505
00:49:20,845 --> 00:49:23,789
It's long and complicated to get artist and publisher answer.

506
00:49:23,789 --> 00:49:28,514
We work with Feel for Music Agency in London.

507
00:49:28,514 --> 00:49:32,019
And thank you again Ben and Glenn, maybe they are here today,

508
00:49:32,019 --> 00:49:34,862
for their help about all those contracts.

509
00:49:35,042 --> 00:49:42,185
Video games, media, can be still seen as a card chase or a gunfight only.

510
00:49:42,185 --> 00:49:46,167
So we have to explain a lot what we are doing, and the type of game we are creating.

511
00:49:46,167 --> 00:49:51,028
I write letters for the artists, show some images, explain our philosophy.

512
00:49:52,130 --> 00:49:56,975
But it's changing very quickly nowadays, so it's really cool for all the artists.

513
00:49:56,975 --> 00:50:03,742
Again, this process you've just seen here occurs when everything works perfectly.

514
00:50:03,742 --> 00:50:10,910
In reality, it can also be like we don't have enough time to listen to all the music we would.

515
00:50:10,910 --> 00:50:12,591
Nobody agrees with you, never.

516
00:50:14,034 --> 00:50:19,258
Each time you test on a sequence it doesn't work, but in your mind it was just perfect.

517
00:50:19,258 --> 00:50:21,580
You check the price and it's too expensive.

518
00:50:23,110 --> 00:50:27,233
And let's say now that everything is working great,

519
00:50:27,233 --> 00:50:29,455
every camera shot fits perfectly the song,

520
00:50:29,455 --> 00:50:31,216
you manage to deal the price,

521
00:50:31,216 --> 00:50:34,579
and in the end, the artist say no.

522
00:50:34,579 --> 00:50:37,641
So, of course, it's not always like that,

523
00:50:37,641 --> 00:50:39,663
with those steps in this specific order.

524
00:50:39,663 --> 00:50:42,045
Every case is really different,

525
00:50:42,045 --> 00:50:44,207
but it's for sure a very long process

526
00:50:44,207 --> 00:50:46,969
dealing with financial, legal, and creative aspects.

527
00:50:51,245 --> 00:50:59,470
First of all, you can see the names of the different artists behind the artworks we have seen during this presentation.

528
00:50:59,470 --> 00:51:03,772
We wanted to thank them for the wonderful work they have done.

529
00:51:03,772 --> 00:51:11,796
As a conclusion, working on the music and how we integrate it in our games is one of the things I prefer in Life is Strange projects.

530
00:51:11,796 --> 00:51:18,860
It's something very long and difficult, but it's like alchemy, and when it works, it's really, really powerful.

531
00:51:20,086 --> 00:51:21,967
Let's end with some advice.

532
00:51:21,967 --> 00:51:24,128
You can of course follow them or not.

533
00:51:24,128 --> 00:51:29,190
Every project and every team is really different.

534
00:51:29,190 --> 00:51:36,213
So first of all, the most important for us is don't use too much music.

535
00:51:38,865 --> 00:51:42,927
Even if we love it, the main danger for us is to put too much music in our game.

536
00:51:42,927 --> 00:51:46,809
We have to be really careful with that.

537
00:51:46,809 --> 00:51:52,491
We really believe that it always be better to have some at very important moments.

538
00:51:52,491 --> 00:51:57,554
We have seen too many games that have destroyed the strength of a musical score by putting

539
00:51:57,554 --> 00:52:01,196
it everywhere.

540
00:52:01,196 --> 00:52:07,259
For the little ones, do not create a jokebox.

541
00:52:08,467 --> 00:52:15,731
Do not select a song only because you love it.

542
00:52:15,731 --> 00:52:19,973
It's really important to always communicate with the other teams.

543
00:52:19,973 --> 00:52:25,376
Even if the music is great by itself, it could not work if the scenes and the design are

544
00:52:25,376 --> 00:52:26,337
not prepared for it.

545
00:52:30,496 --> 00:52:33,919
Third one, don't ask too many people for feedback

546
00:52:33,919 --> 00:52:38,143
and choose the songs wisely.

547
00:52:38,143 --> 00:52:40,505
Music is very personal and survey

548
00:52:40,505 --> 00:52:43,488
can generate a lot of frustration in a team.

549
00:52:43,488 --> 00:52:48,533
Be sure you have a general coherence in your music.

550
00:52:48,533 --> 00:52:51,575
Having only one people is the best way to achieve that.

551
00:52:51,575 --> 00:52:53,577
It could be the main composer

552
00:52:53,577 --> 00:52:56,080
or the creative director like for us.

553
00:52:59,335 --> 00:53:07,484
And last one, always have a plan B, even a C. Easy one, but you have so many unexpected

554
00:53:07,484 --> 00:53:10,308
events and you really have to be prepared.

555
00:53:10,308 --> 00:53:18,076
Thank you everyone for listening.

556
00:53:18,076 --> 00:53:19,077
Thank you for your presence.

